{
  "texts": [
    "When it comes to analyzing meaning in text, Kirgil and Voyer (2022) However, as Mohr (1998) was prescient to point out in his foundational article, \"Measuring meaning structures\", it is not enough to leverage high-powered computational tools to analyze texts, because the results of such analyses must still be interpreted in a humanistic and qualitative way.",
    "At present, computational sociological studies often adopt a more quantitative logic emphasizing the central tendencies of discourse, thereby limiting the possibilities for the interpretation of meaning (Nelson 2021).",
    "As an alternative to approaches that use computational methods to bring a quantitative logic to text analysis, Nelson's (2020) work on computational grounded theory is a prime example of adopting a qualitative logic in computational analyses, where the focus is on using computational methods to assist in interpretation (see also Nelson, 2022; Nelson, 2021).",
    "When used interpretively, ChatGPT and other large language models combine the scale that computational techniques allow for with the researcher's qualitative logic.",
    "This integrated approach is in line with other developments in computational sociology, which leverages tools like network analysis and machine learning to better understand the meaning of text."
  ]
}